Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 22d268cb2c0bc00676d08c79f6ab8958bee74a25

I'm in favor of making this change.  

Redfish aggregation is another in-development feature that would greatly benefit from not having hard coded IDs.  The hard coded IDs are preventing adding prefixes to URIs to explicitly denote when a request is meant for the aggregating BMC.  Those prefixes would also prevent possible collisions between local and satellite resources.

The fwupdate service file(bmcweb/redfish-core/lib/update_service.hpp) has one hardcoded system name entry -
      item["@odata.id"] = "/redfish/v1/Systems/system/Bios"
is this also needs to be changed?

Given that we still only support "system" this code is still correct.  It would need to be changed if we ever supported more than one system, like you're doing in your patch, and is one of the reasons why I recommended you keep the first host named "system" for a while.
yeah got it and agreed.There are no redfish route handling calls (/redfish/v1/Systems/<str>) on the fwupdate service file. so it is not needed here.

Because I was attempting to keep the patch small, but a number of the managers routes are more complex and deserve their own patchset given the complexity.  It's also not an immediate priority, whereas fixing Systems is blocking multi-host.
ACK. Consider adding them into the this sentence?

would "moving these to routes that match the redfish spec would likely
meant that we could generate this code in the future at some point ..."  be a better wording?

Yes. 

I didn't find routing in the Redfish spec but routing exists in this project.
since the routes are adapted to support multi-host route names and also error checking is added for invalid routes, This change Looks good to be.
have you tested it on a system?  that’s what it was waiting on
I have verified this change in yosemiteV2 platform and changes are working as expected.
did you run service validator on it?
Not used it. I have used the curl commands provided in REDFISH-cheatsheet.md and verified the relevant routes and info available in the yosemitev2 platform.
ok, then service validator is the next step that needs run on this patch.  It's on my list, but if it's a higher priority for you, feel free to go ahead and test it.
Naveen, I can also help run validator on the system that I have. Let me know if you don't get the chance.

Naveen,
If you intend to work on Redfish patches in the future, you will need to learn to use the redfish service validator.

Naveen, I suspect that this patchset is the highest priority for you and your team, given that it's the next step for multi-host development.

As always, I'm happy to test things, but my backlog is long these days.
Thanks Ed,I will validate with service validator in our platform and update the results.
